And that's it.
<p>There are lots of references across multiple sources for ghost ships, most of which could be described as &quot;decaying&quot;, but there is simply no way to sufficiently verify that that reference is to the <em>Voyager</em> specifically. I think it is more or less impossible to track her movements across the seas.</p>
<p>It is interesting to note that the Commission decided at some point to &quot;feed&quot; the contagion aboard the <em>Voyager</em>. Without access to Trower, we may never know what the purpose was for such a move. Maybe it was out of a sense of guilt for what happened to Faulkner? It's also possible that the Board of Regents simply decided that &quot;feeding&quot; the <em>Voyager</em> was better than having it prey upon other ships. If giving Faulkner a bunch of spares was enough to keep him from sinking other ships, it was probably a win-win.</p>
<p>I heard that you are looking into possible connections with <a href="/scp-3862">SCP-3862</a> as a potential avenue to developing an antigen. If this is indeed the same (or similar) disease, then I am grateful to Faulkner for keeping it off land for as long as he has.</p>
<p>Regardless, it is my recommendation that we continue to follow the Commission's example in this. If we can't cure it and can't contain it, feeding it might be our only option.</p>
<p>Respectfully,</p>
<p>Dr. Cezar Iliescu<br />
Research Head, SCP-5862<br />
Dept. of Nautical Anomalies</p>
